!front: When does equality hold in the triangle inequality $|a+b| \le |a| + |b|$?
!back: Equality holds when $a$ and $b$ have the same sign or one of them is zero.
~~~

!id: 2C7nY6M5Fp
!front: Prove the reverse triangle inequality.
!back:
The reverse triangle inequality states:

\[
\big||a| - |b|\big| \le |a - b|
\]

Proof:

Apply triangle inequality to $(a - b) + b = a$:

\[
|a| = |(a-b)+b| \le |a-b| + |b|
\]

Rearranging:

\[
|a| - |b| \le |a-b|
\]

Swap $a,b$ to get:

\[
|b| - |a| \le |a-b|
\]

Combining both gives:

\[
\big||a| - |b|\big| \le |a-b|
\]
~~~

